== Unencycplopaedic slang ==

The statement that "the downtown core of Ottawa was placed on lockdown" is unencyclopaedic slang, and poor English. "Central Ottawa was subject to unprecedented security measures" would be a more accurate statement.[[User:Royalcourtier|Royalcourtier]] ([[User talk:Royalcourtier|talk]]) 07:24, 7 April 2016 (UTC)
::what is wrong with lockdown?  A similar thing happened after the Boston Marathon bombing and the same term was used. All buildings closed etc. [[User:Legacypac|Legacypac]] ([[User talk:Legacypac|talk]]) 07:49, 7 April 2016 (UTC)

:"Lockdown" is, in fact, the term used by the [http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/ottawa-shooting-a-day-of-chaos-leaves-soldier-gunman-dead-1.2808710 CBC], [http://news.nationalpost.com/news/canada/soldier-shot-outside-of-parliament-at-national-war-memorial-active-shooter-believed-to-be-on-the-loose National Post], [http://globalnews.ca/news/1628313/shots-fired-at-war-memorial-in-ottawa-says-witness/ Global Television], [http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/parliament-shooting/article21217602/?page=all The Globe and Mail], [http://ottawacitizen.com/news/local-news/soldier-shot-at-war-memorial-in-ottawa Ottawa Citizen], [http://ottawacitizen.com/news/local-news/soldier-shot-at-war-memorial-in-ottawa CTV], [http://www.bbc.com/news/live/world-us-canada-29728503 BBC], [https://www.yahoo.com/news/canada-parliament-attacks-154056871.html Yahoo!/Agence France-Presse], etc.  In fact, the usage of "lockdown" to describe what happened is pretty much universal. [[User:Resolute|Reso]][[User Talk:Resolute|lute]] 14:41, 7 April 2016 (UTC)

:: "Central Ottawa was subject to unprecedented security measures" is so vague as to be meaningless.  Were there more police officers on patrol?  Tanks in the street?  Mounties going door-to-door?  "Lockdown" is a common and easily understood word. [[User:Mr Serjeant Buzfuz|Mr Serjeant Buzfuz]] ([[User talk:Mr Serjeant Buzfuz|talk]]) 03:51, 8 April 2016 (UTC)

